Who is ROSALÍA? - Quick Facts!

  • 2-time Grammy Award and 12-time Latin Grammy Award winning artist and producer

  • breakout album “El Mal Querer” meshed an innovative fusion of Flamenco and other timeless music styles of Spain

  • historic first-ever Best New Artist Grammy nomination for a Spanish language artist

  • global press dubbing MOTOMAMI: “a visionary masterpiece… as provocative and risky as it is creative… the most thrilling, forward-thinking music we’ll hear all year…[and] one of the most ambitious albums of the decade — regardless of genre”.

  • MOTOMAMI debuted at #1 on Spotify’s Global Album Chart, (a first-ever accomplishment for a Spanish artist),

  • the strongest Billboard chart debut of any 2022 Latin album

  • highest Metacritic rating (95) of any album released that year.

info from official website: https://www.rosalia.com/

Data preparation

#removing records with the same track names
ROSALÍA <- ROSALÍA |> distinct(track_name, .keep_all = TRUE)
#filter out track names that include "live at"
ROSALÍA <- ROSALÍA |> filter(!grepl("Live At|Live Acoustic","Live en el Palau Sant Jordi",track_name))

Graphs.

ROSALÍA throughout years expanded the scope of her music. Her first album Los Ángeles appears to me as the most traditional, using many flamenco elements. Her second album is still true to these elements but adds new modern twists. Finally, MOTOMAMI represents a change from traditional to more experimental music, since it was meant to be a concept album.

Due to these changes in style, I would first like to look at different danceability of ROSALÍA’s albums.

#changing album name from characters to factors
ROSALÍA$album_name <- as.factor(ROSALÍA$album_name)
#plotting a boxplot
ggplot(ROSALÍA, aes(x=album_name, y=danceability, color=album_name))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(title= "Energy of ROSALÍA's albums", x="Album Name", y="Energy")

These results do not surprise me. Based on her live perfomances of Los Ángeles songs, she is not dancing much, yet her music is very expressive in tone and emotion.

(You can watch her live performance of Los Ángeles album here! https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=varnR9n_wfc)

El Mal Querer and MOTOMAMI are certainly much more danceable albums.

ROSALÍA’s last album (MOTOMAMI) had much more aggressive elements, such as distorted drums, autotune, jazz-features and drawn to a great extent from the reggaeton music, which to me seems a bit more fast-paced than flamenco used in El Mal Querer.

That’s why I would like to compare the tempo levels of the El Mal Querer and MOTOMAMI+ albums.

ROSALÍA$album_name <- as.factor(ROSALÍA$album_name)
#I want to select only El Mal Querer and MOTOMAMI + albums
selected_albums <- c("El Mal Querer", "MOTOMAMI +")
El_MOTOMAMI <- ROSALÍA[ROSALÍA$album_name %in% selected_albums,]

#plotting a boxplot
ggplot(El_MOTOMAMI, aes(x=album_name, y=tempo, color=album_name))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(title= "Tempo of ROSALÍA's albums", x="Album Name", y="Tempo")

It is visible that MOTOMAMI is much “faster” album on average in comparison to El Mal Querer.

MOTOMAMI boxplot has also a larger IQR, indicating greater spread and variety among songs when it comes to tempo.

It is indeed very experimental album, and that’s why I would be interested to see what is variance between individual songs on this album in terms of valence and energy. (my favourite song is indicated on the graph too!)

#I want to select only MOTOMAMI + album
selected_album_1 <- c("MOTOMAMI +")
MOTOMAMI_album <- ROSALÍA[ROSALÍA$album_name %in% selected_album_1,]
subgroup <- c("SAOKO")
SAOKO_track <- ROSALÍA[ROSALÍA$track_name %in% subgroup,]

ggplot(MOTOMAMI_album, aes(x = valence, y = energy))+
  geom_point(color = "red")+
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.5, color= "grey")+
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0.5, color="grey")+
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1))+
  geom_text(data=SAOKO_track, aes(label=track_name))

  labs(title= "Relationship between Valence and Energy of songs on MOTOMAMI+ album", x="Valence", y="Energy")

Most of her songs according to this graph are situated on the “sad” part of the graph.

I wanted to see three songs that have the lowest valence and energy from the album.

Interesting! The first two did not personally surprise me but the third song does not sound very sad for me.

But anyways! Now I would like to zoom out and look how ROSALÍA’s energy levels has changed throughout the time with her albums:

ROSALÍA$album_release_year <- as.factor(ROSALÍA$album_release_year)

ggplot(ROSALÍA, aes(x = album_release_year, y = energy))+
  stat_summary(fun.y = mean, geom = "point")+
  stat_summary(fun.data = mean_cl_normal, geom = "errorbar")+
  stat_summary(fun.y = mean,aes(group=1), geom = "line", linetype = "dashed")

It seems that her energy levels were rising, most steeply between her first and second album, but also a bit between second and third!

Does this have any effect on duration of the tracks? Maybe she has more energy because he tracks are shorter and she does not get tired as quickly? Let’s see:

ggplot(ROSALÍA, aes(x = duration_ms, y = energy,))+
   geom_point()+
   geom_smooth(method= "lm", alpha = 0.1, fill= "blue")+
   labs(title= "Relationship between Energy and Duration of ROSALÍA's songs", x="Duration", y="Energy")

This seems to show that higher duration decreases the energy levels of the tracks!

Or maybe she used to sing much more during her earlier tracks and got tired more quickly? Let’s check how the speechines of her songs changed:

ggplot(ROSALÍA, aes(x = album_name, y = speechiness))+
         stat_summary(fun.y = mean, geom = "bar", fill = "lightblue") +
         stat_summary(fun.data = mean_cl_normal, geom = "errorbar")

This shows that the MOTOMAMI is the album in which she sings the most!

Bottom Line

So there it is! It seems, based on the statistics, that ROSALÍA’s latest album MOTOMAMI is the one with the highest speechiness, energy and tempo out of all her albums! A closer look at the individual songs show how dispersed they are in terms of their energy and valence, seemingly evoking different range of emotions.

Based on her interview for Billboard, ROSALÍA wanted her album to have “roller coaster energy that is high and low, high and low.” (full interview here: https://www.billboard.com/music/latin/rosalia-motomami-interview-1235047442/)

I think she did a great job with that, and these statistics show that!
